## 9. Natural collocations — don't reify yes / no / stop / ask

Do **not** turn limits, refusals, and requests into weird protocol nouns, and do **not** pair ordinary English verbs with the wrong object.

**The core problem:** some verbs expect a person or a concrete thing. Feeding them an abstract kink-noun makes the line stumble.

**Bad (wrong frame + reified noun):**
> I cheated on the stop you asked for *(cheat on → person)*
> I'm proud of the no / I hated the no at one a.m. / He obeyed a no
> Got your stop / your three nos / That no counted
> part of the step / soft reports to stand on / that thing wants one more step
> the smallest version of the ask / the quiet ask / Thank me for the almost
> I'm punishing the jealousy *(punish a person, not an emotion-as-object)*

**Good (keep verbs as verbs; name the act):**
> I still feel like I cheated on you, even though we stopped where you asked
> I'm proud I said no / I hated that you said no at one a.m. / he didn't touch because she'd said no
> I got your texts — stop, please sleep / you saying no three times / When you said no, I stopped him
> part of what we do next / enough coffee-and-kiss details that you can handle more / Now I want one more thing from you
> shrinking what he wanted until they could say yes / quietly asking / Thank me for stopping you
> I'm punishing you for getting jealous

**Heuristic:** if the noun is just a yes/no/stop/ask/almost/step wearing a definite article, rewrite with the actual speech or act (`said no`, `stopped where you asked`, `almost came`). Findom SKUs and clear product talk (`unlock fee`, tip notes) are fine when the reader still knows what is being bought.

### Verb-first kink framing — do the act to him; don't SKU the kink

When a beat is about **her doing something to him** (especially cuckolding, denial, mean-girl humiliation), prefer an **active verb aimed at the sub** over a **reified kink noun**.

**Bad (reified noun / SKU):**
> It's about the report — which is kinda cute and mean at the same time?
> waiting for a report / gave the full report / survive the report / the hogtie report

**Good (verb does something to him — land once, then vary):**
> It's about making you hear it — which is kinda cute and mean at the same time? *(definition beat; use sparingly)*
> I'll tell you everything after / walked him through coffee / described the hike while he stayed in the panties
> braced for whatever she'd bring home in words / that fact sits next to us every time I sit you down like this
> What followed was not a telling from across town. It was watching with nowhere to hide.

**Why "making" matters (when you use it):** the verb isn't neutral narration — it implies **dominance**. She isn't filing paperwork; she is *making* him take the knowledge. That lands the "mean" half of cute-and-mean and goes hand in hand with cuckolding. Prefer that frame for the **one definitional beat**, not as a pasted refrain.

**Do not paste the same verb-frame.** `making you hear it` / `made him hear` / `make you hear` stacked across chapters becomes a soft house code — same failure mode as `the report`. After the definition lands, switch to ordinary telling verbs that still do something to him (`tell you everything`, `walked him through`, `described`, `sit you down`, `bring home in words`) without inventing a new SKU noun.

### Plain act verbs — not syllabus nouns

When a character quotes research or names a first escalation, prefer **ordinary verbs that do the act** over **workshop labels** that sound like a kink handout.

**Bad (syllabus / workshop noun):**
> visual attention counts as a first step
> accidental flashes are still a kind of offering
> saying yes to small attention
> duration is a choice
> Insane is our genre / finished the syllabus / invent a whole genre

**Good (plain act):**
