> saying yes to little things like that / saying yes when a boy asks for your number
> how long you let a hand stay is a choice
> We're past sane / finished what he had her read / turn homework into this

**Heuristic:** if the noun could sit in a bullet list titled "escalation stages" without naming a body or an act (`attention`, `offering`, `duration`, `genre`, `syllabus`, `visual X`), rewrite with who did what. Cute research-girlfriend voice can still cite "the article" — the **cited idea** should be plain English.

Quoting an article once in ordinary English is fine. Do **not** mint private house jargon (`soft things`, `soft steps`, `the report` as a reusable kink SKU) and reuse it as if the reader already knows the code.

## 10. No obscure house jargon — and don't wear out stock phrases

Do **not** invent private euphemisms that only make sense inside the story's own codebook, then reuse them until they feel like a brand. If a phrase means "take it slow," "coffee only," "kissing but not sex," or "denial is getting unbearable," **say that**. Soft / cute voice is fine; cryptic house slang is not.

**Also:** do not let one cute refrain do the same job four times in a row. Either vary it with a clearer concrete meaning, or cut the repeats.

**Banned / scrub patterns (and close cousins):**
> soft things / soft steps / soft first / soft dating / soft dates / soft reports / soft restart / soft flirting *(as a reusable label)*
> the report / a report / reports *(as the reusable name of the cuckold-telling kink — prefer a sparse definition beat + ordinary telling verbs; see §9)*
> visual attention / a kind of offering / small attention / duration is a choice *(syllabus nouns — prefer plain acts: letting boys look, letting him see, saying yes to little things; see §9)*
> Insane is our genre / finished the syllabus / invent a whole genre *(meta workshop labels for the kink arc)*
> little steps *(as a repeated house code after the articles have already been explained once)*
> the waiting gets too loud / cute and terrible / for your own good *(when it stands in for a named escalation)*
> spitting seemed mean *(as a copy-paste swallow excuse every oral telling)*
> iced tea / coffee / kissing "as if that was the promise" metaphors stacked the same way every beat

**Do:**
- Name the act or limit: coffee that stays coffee; kissing only; no mouths yet; denial in the cage; go further — mouths, more texts, maybe more than mouths
- Quote an article once if the character is researching (`going one level at a time`), then speak in concrete acts afterward
- Keep intentional nicknames that cut (`soft boy` as Sir's emasculation brand) — those are labels with a job, not vague pacing codes
- If a refrain is character voice (`sorryyy`, sticky notes), keep it sparse; do not let one swallow-excuse or one metaphor become the whole telling style
- For cuckold aftercare/telling beats: land verb-first dominance once if needed (`making you hear it`), then ordinary telling aimed at him — not a pasted refrain and not a SKU noun (`the report`)
- When citing articles: plain act verbs (`letting boys look`), not syllabus nouns (`visual attention`, `offering`, `duration`)

**Don't:**
- Treat `soft X` as a reusable category for "gentle version of the kink"
- Assume the reader remembers what `soft things` meant three chapters ago
- Paste the same witty excuse or thesis smile into every escalation beat
- Reify the telling kink as `the report` / `reports` across chapters

**Bad:**
> We should stick to soft things for a while.
> Soft steps first. Soft reports. Soft restart.
> It's about the report. / waiting for a report. / gave the hogtie report.
> It's about making you hear it. *(× every chapter)* / made him hear every detail. *(×4)*
> I swallowed because spitting seemed mean. *(×4 across chapters)*
> Text me if the waiting gets too loud.

**Good:**
> Coffee and kissing only for a while — no mouths, no sex.
> Start with shorter clothes and coffee dates that stay coffee, then kissing, then touching.
> It's about making you hear it. *(once)* / I'll tell you everything after. / described the hike while he stayed in the panties.
> I swallowed — I didn't want to spit in his car. / I swallowed the same way I did with Connor.
> Text me if denial starts driving you crazy.

**Heuristic when editing:** if a phrase could mean three different acts depending on chapter, rewrite it. If the same colorful excuse or metaphor appears more than twice for the same beat type, vary or delete.

Applies to **all** authors. Cute/inquisitive girlfriends are the highest risk for inventing soft house codes; Domme product talk is fine when the SKU is still clear.

## 11. Chapters (optional)

Most stories are single-chapter (`pages` only). Multi-chapter stories:

- Keep one catalog entry (browse / author / home). Never register extra chapters as separate stories.
- Set `firstChapterName` + `firstChapterSummary` for the opening `pages` body, plus `chapters: [{ name, summary, pages }, …]` for the rest.
- **Every chapter has a name and a short summary.** Summaries are chapter-specific blurbs for the story-page dropdown — **not** a copy of the catalog `excerpt`.
- The story page shows a chapter dropdown (name only) below tags and above page pagination; minutes and that chapter's summary appear directly under the dropdown for the selected chapter.
- Read time on cards and the story kicker is the **sum** of all chapters.
- Each chapter should still meet the 5-minute minimum on its own when practical.

## 12. Length and registration (unchanged)

- Minimum **5-minute** read: ≥ **1150** words of body text at **230 WPM** (`node scripts/count-words.mjs` / `getReadingMinutes`). No `UNDER 5 MIN`. Multi-chapter: count all chapters; prefer each chapter ≥5 min.
- Match `Story` shape in `src/types.ts`; register in `src/data/stories/index.ts`.
- Follow the selected author’s `writingStyle` in `src/data/authors.ts`, except where this rule file conflicts (ages, consent theatre, banned names, no plot-summary, sexual excerpts, male panties as emasculation/humiliation, fragment spam, no therapy-speak desire, natural collocations, no obscure house jargon / worn-out stock phrases, plain English / no AI gibberish, aka Cock Bobber gold-standard ban, cuckold gaslighting craft / prose ban) — **this file wins**.

